body:
I tried this code:
[playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2021&gist=ad21ff588d5588bec14d4d9b9f7d114e)
```rust
type Alias1<'a, T> = &'a mut dyn FnMut() -> T;
type Alias2<T> = dyn FnMut() -> T;

trait Foo {
    fn foo<T>(&self, t: Alias1<'_, T>) -> T {
        t()
    }

    fn bar<T>(&self, t: &'_ mut Alias2<T>) -> T {
        t()
    }

    fn test1<T, F: FnMut() -> T>(&self, mut f: F) -> T {
        self.foo(&mut f)
    }

    fn test2<T, F: FnMut() -> T>(&self, mut f: F) -> T {
        self.bar(&mut f)
    }
}
```
But this leads to a compilation error in the second case
```
error[E0310]: the parameter type `F` may not live long enough
  --> src\lib.rs:18:18
   |
18 |         self.bar(&mut f)
   |                  ^^^^^^ ...so that the type `F` will meet its required lifetime bounds
   |
help: consider adding an explicit lifetime bound...
   |
17 |     fn test2<T, F: FnMut() -> T + 'static>(&self, mut f: F) -> T {
   |                                 +++++++++
```
I don't understand why this is happening. Is this an error or is it expected?
